{
  "answer": "No direct reference explicitly weighing *punya* (merit) against *paap* (sin/demerit) using those precise Sanskrit terms appears in the Smṛti translations of the Falsafa corpus (e.g., Manu, Yājñavalkya, Viṣṇu, Bṛhaspati, etc.). The English translations render these concepts as \"merit\" and \"demerit\"/\"sin,\" with moral accounting implied through rebirths, penances balancing faults (e.g., Manu 11.44–53), or equal fruits of actions (e.g., Manu 5.53, where sacrificing for 100 years equals abstaining from meat).[^1][^2]\n\nA close Smṛti rule balancing merit (*puṇya-phala*) against demerit (*apuṇya-phala*) as equivalent shares occurs in Bṛhaspati Smṛti:\n\n> The wife is remembered as half the body, equal in the fruit of merit and demerit.[^3]\n\nHere, a wife's virtuous acts (*merit*) are weighed precisely equal against her faults (*demerit*) to her husband's, such that both share the karmic fruits identically—like halves of one body. This underscores spousal moral interdependence in Smṛti ethics, beyond mere transactionality.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 11, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/#p-7f8ce7). Penances expiate sins; unintentional ones via Veda study, intentional via rites.\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 5, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-89d810). \"The fruit of the merit of these two [acts] is equal.\"\n[^3]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-0e8ca8). A virtuous wife attains her husband's welfare whether she immolates or survives.",
